"Similar vein, but should move the checks out of the `tests/*.py` for `jsonschema.validate()` and move it into the `hfpdf()` call. E.G.\r\n\r\n```python\r\nclass hfpdf(object):\r\n    def __init__(self, spec, **config_kwargs):\r\n        self.config = modelconfig.from_spec(spec,**config_kwargs)\r\n        self.spec = spec\r\n```\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n```python\r\nclass hfpdf(object):\r\n    def __init__(self, spec, **config_kwargs):\r\n        jsonschema.validate(spec, schema)\r\n        self.config = modelconfig.from_spec(spec,**config_kwargs)\r\n        self.spec = spec\r\n```\r\n\r\nso it's always checking it each time a spec is loaded. This reduces a significant amount of checking in the rest of the code.\n\nyes... so I would propose a standalone validation function\r\n\r\n```\r\ndef validate(spec):\r\n```\r\n\r\nwhich at first can be a simple shim for `jsonschema.validate`\r\n\r\n```\r\ndef validate(spec):\r\n    try:\r\n       return jsonschema.validate(spec)\r\n    except jsonschema.ValidationError:\r\n      raise pyhf.exceptions.SpecificationError('does not pass schema. [some formatting to make sense of schema errors]')\r\n```\r\n\r\nthat raises perhaps a `pyhf.SpecificationError` exception and which has a digestible description of what is wrong and otherwise returns `None` \r\n\r\nlater we will add more semantic checks. this will also allow standalone validation without object construction e.g. for a cli tool `hf-validate spec.json`\n\nYes. The jsonschema errors are actually really clear. (Try it out, it's\nreally nice).\n\nG\nOn Sat, Apr 14, 2018 at 14:34 Lukas <notifications@github.com> wrote:\n\n> yes... so I would propose a standalone validation function\n>\n> def validate(spec):\n>\n> which at first can be a simple shim for jsonschema.validate\n>\n> def validate(spec):\n>     try:\n>        return jsonschema.validate(spec)\n>     except jsonschema.ValidationError:\n>       raise pyhf.exceptions.SpecificationError('does not pass schema. [some formatting to make sense of schema errors]')\n>\n> that raises perhaps a pyhf.exceptions.SpecificationError exception which\n> has a digestible description of what is wrong.\n>\n> later we will add more semantic checks.\n>\n> \u2014\n> You are receiving this because you commented.\n>\n>\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/diana-hep/pyhf/issues/118#issuecomment-381354670>, or mute\n> the thread\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AAuei-U0XlrjgdTKM6JK-R7cEOgWydCKks5tok8rgaJpZM4TVLo1>\n> .\n>\n-- \nGiordon Stark\n\n\nActually, just realized this may not be a perfect idea. Let's suppose someone is adding a custom modifier (some theorist or bayesist), the spec validation automatically added will block their custom modifier -- effectively. A (perhaps decent) solution is to add a default `validate_spec=True` to the `hfpdf.__init__(...)` so that it can be turned off in \"expert mode\" or something.\n\nyes that's what we do in `yadage` as well. e.g. while yadage workflows adhere to a JSON schema you can run with `--validate false` and it will be skipped. I think that's a good pattern "